# Windows Firewall Investigation

## Goal

Learn how Windows Defender Firewall controls network traffic by exploring existing firewall rules, creating custom rules, and verifying how those rules affect network communication.

## Skills Practiced

- Windows Defender Firewall
- Firewall Rule Analysis
- Network Profiles
- ICMP
- Connectivity Testing
- Troubleshooting

## What I Learned

- The difference between inbound and outbound firewall rules.
- How Windows Firewall organizes rules by Public, Private, Domain, and All network profiles.
- Why applications often have multiple firewall rules (TCP, UDP, and different profiles).
- How to create, test, disable, and remove a custom firewall rule.
- How firewall profiles affect whether a rule is applied.
- How to verify firewall changes using `ping`.

## Project Files

- 5-Windows Firewall.pdf

## Reflection

This project helped me understand that Windows Firewall is much more than simply allowing or blocking programs. I 
learned how rules are organized, why applications can have multiple rules, and how network profiles determine when 
a rule is applied. One of the biggest lessons came from troubleshooting my own test rule. At first it appeared that 
my ICMP rule wasn't working, but after investigating I realized my rule only applied to the Private profile while 
my network was using the Public profile. Updating the rule fixed the problem and reinforced the importance of testing 
and troubleshooting rather than assuming a configuration is correct.

## More to Explore

- Create rules using specific ports instead of protocols.
- Explore outbound firewall rules in more detail.
- Learn how Windows Firewall integrates with Windows Defender.
- Use PowerShell to view and manage firewall rules.
